@endnode
@node spelabout
@title "Where did this amazing piece of software come from?"

      Speller was programmed by John Mason in ACE BASIC, which is a great
   BASIC compiler for the Amiga.  It's on Aminet, so get it if you like
   BASIC, or even if you don't!  This version was completed on October 31
   1995 (or something like that).

      Speller is a program to help you learn quickly and easily how to spell
   words.  It's great for students who have weekly spelling lists (like me!
   aarrgh!) or parents who want to ensure their children learn to spell
   at an early age or at any age.

      Go back to the @{"Speller" link spllr} link to learn more.
@endnode
@node spelsetup
@title "Setup - Format 30 disks and double click the Install icon"

      Erm.. Just kidding about the 30 disks :)..  In fact it's so simple
   to install, you don't even need to read this.  If you've gotten this
   Amigaguide® document unarchived then the rest of the files are ready
   too.  The only thing you need to do is double click the Install icon
   which will assign Speller: to whichever directory it's in.  (Ignore
   that explanation if you have no idea what I'm saying.)
   You'll need to do this after every reboot unless you add the line
   'Assign Speller: Work:Speller' to your S:User-Startup or S:Startup-
   Sequence file.  Just remember to change 'Work:Speller' to the directory
   that you have Speller on your system.

      Even simpler though, if you have Kickstart 2.04 or higher, you can
   just drag the Install icon into the WbStartup drawer on your boot disk.

@endnode
@node spelreq
@title "Requirements: 060, 20MB Chip, 100MB fast, 10gig HD, 4 Joysticks"

      Speller isn't a very demanding program.  It even runs under Kickstart
   1.3!  There are only a few things that you do need:


             The necessary files for speech:

                    L:Speak-Handler
                    Devs:Narrator.Device
                    Libs:Translator.Library

             If you're using KS 1.3, you'll need the Arp.Library in your
   Libs: directory (which is the libs/ directory on the disk you booted
   with, i.e. 'DH0:Libs/Arp.Library')

      Other than that, you should be fine.  Oh yeah, you might also need
   the iff.library or the iffparse.library in your Libs: directory.  If the
   title screen/graphics don't appear, then that might be why.


@endnode
@node spelwords
@title "Making your own word files and how they work"

   The easiest way to make your own word files to use in Speller is to
use the other program, @{"Spelled" link spled}, to enter the words, but if you want to
do it the hard way, read this:

   Speller provides 2 lines for each word.  One is for the actual word,
and one is an optional pronunciation line.  This is because some words
are pronounced incorrectly by the Amiga's speech system.  If you have
such a word, you can add a pronunciation to it so that it will be pronounced
correctly by Speller.

   The word files are plain old ASCII text, so they can be edited by any
regular text editor.  Here's how the files are set up.
The first line is ALWAYS the first word.  It may contain spaces, but no
punctuation, since Speller won't allow punctuation to be typed by the user.
The next line can be one of two things:

  A: The next word, which must follow the same rules as the first word, no
     punctuation.
  B: The pronunciation for the previous word.  This MUST be enclosed in
     [square] brackets.  If not, it will be treated as the next word,
     which will cause all sorts of problems.

     You must have ten words (not counting pronunciations) in each word file.
   Any less than that will probably cause some kind of an error, and Speller
   will tell you that you tried to load an invalid word file.
   The next version of Speller should allow you to set the number of words
   in each file.

@endnode
@node spelusage
@title "Using Speller - Insert tab 'A' into slot 'B' and press button C"

   To run Speller, double click its icon.  After a few moments, you should
see a screen with three gadgets in the middle of the screen.
This is where you choose whether you want to load a word file or use
the default words (or quit).  Click on the appropriate gadget.
If you chose to load a word file, you'll get a file requester asking you
to select which file to load.  By the way, you can run Speller from the Shell
and give it a command line argument in the form of a word file.  For
example, if Speller and words.txt were in the current directory,
then you could type 'Speller words.txt' without the 's, and then Speller
would skip the main screen and load the words.

Once you've chosen the file you want, or if you chose to use the defaults,
you'll be presented with another screen, which asks you whether you want
to start the spelling or preview the words (or, again, quit).
Selecting preview will show you the words you're about to spell.
To start the spelling, click the Start gadget.

Now you're hopefully looking at the main screen, and Speller has just
asked you how to spell the first word. (Turn up your volume if it isn't
audible.)  Before you start, take a look at the screen.
On the left hand side, you'll see two boxes that show you information about
your score such as percent, your score, total words, etc.  At the bottom
of the screen is a long box which will display messages at certain points
during spelling.  The last message was probably 'Let the games begin!'.
Near the top right hand corner of the screen is the input box.  This
is where you enter the spelling of the current word.  You don't need
to click here to begin typing, just type and your text will appear.
You can use backspace to delete the last character, and ESC to erase the
whole text. At the bottom right hand corner are two gadgets, Repeat, and
the familiar Quit.  Repeat will re-say the current word just in case you
didn't catch it the last time.  Quit will quit Speller.  Period.

  Now that you know what everything does, you can start!  By now,
Speller will probably have already asked you to spell the first word.
So, click the Repeat gadget to hear the word again.
Now, type in the spelling of the word.  You'll see the letters appear in
the input box.  Press enter when you're done.
If you spelled the word correctly, your score will be upped, and you'll
be asked to spell the next word.  If you spelled the word incorrectly,
Speller will let you know, and then it will spell the word for you.  The
correct spelling will also be shown in the message box.
Then you'll go on to the next word.
This will continue until you have tried all ten words, and then Speller
will tell you what your score was just in case you didn't notice it in the
score box.  Now just click the left mouse button, and you'll be returned
to the Shell or Workbench.

  The next version will probably allow you to load another set of words or
start over without having to run the program again.
@endnode
@node Spelfuture
@title "Back to the....."

  I had a lot of fun making Speller, especially drawing the screens.
I'd like to improve it in a number of ways, here are a few:

                        - Able-to-set-number-of-word-ness (!)
                        - More default words
                        - Load a new word file or retry last one without
                          reloading the program
                        - Set number of retries for words
                        - More!

  Anyone with some ideas and the ability to send E-mail should contact
me. My address is ah210@ccn.cs.dal.ca if you want to send suggestions or
comments.  NO CHAIN LETTERS PLEASE! :)

  Speller is freeware, but I will gladly accept gifts, and those who do
send me something (email me first) can consider themselves registered users.
More registered users will encourage me to work on new versions.

@endnode
@node spled
@title "Now you can make your own words!  It's easy!  It's Fun!"


        Spelled is a little program that lets you make your own word
      files for the @{"Speller" link spllr} program included in this archive.

        Once you run Spelled, you'll see it's window.  This is where
      everything happens.  There are two text gadgets.  The first is where
      you enter the actual word.  There may be spaces in the word,
      i.e. two words or a phrase, but that is the only punctuation that is
      allowed.  If you do include punctuation like apostrophes or commas,
      they will be used by Speller, but you won't be able to enter them.
      BE SURE TO PRESS ENTER AFTER TYPING THE WORD!!  Otherwise the data
      won't be recorded.  The second gadget is where you enter the optional
      pronunciation for the word in the first text gadget.  This is provided
      because sometimes the Amiga's speech system won't pronounce words
      correctly, so you can type in the word so that it will be pronounced
      correctly.  For example, if the word you had was pioneer, you could
      put something like 'pie on ear' in the pronunciation gadget.  There
      can be punctuation here, since the you don't ever see this in Speller.

        There are seven other gadgets in the window:

    Next Word : This gadget moves to the next word.  There are ten.

    Prev Word : This gadget moves to the previous word.

    New  :   This gadget erases ALL words from memory.

    Load :   This gadget loads a previously saved word file.

    Save :   This gadget saves the words in memory to disk.  It is
             ghosted (unavailable) until all the Word text gadgets
             have something in them.  If they all do and Save is still
             ghosted, then one of the words has a [ at the beginning of it,
             or one of the words is greater than 24 characters.  This limitation
             will hopefully be removed in a future version.
             The [ character is used by Speller to indicate pronunciations,
             so you can't include it as part of a word.  But what word has
             a [ in it anyway?

     Spell : This gadget is available once you have saved your words.  It
             will run Speller as long as you have Speller: assigned correctly
             or if you have double clicked the Install icon.  The words you
             just saved will be loaded into Speller.  Once you quit Speller
             you can continue using Spelled.

      Quit : This gadget quits Speller.  That's it.  No hidden functions or
             anything.

      That's it!  Happy spelling!

@endnode
@node Spched
@title "Speeched - Como esta usted?"



       SpeechEd is a small program similar to Spelled.  Using this program
      you can change everything Speller says.  You can even use it to make
      Speller bi, tri, or multi-lingual!

                           @{"The Gadgets" link spchgds} @{"Usage" link spchusg}
@endnode
@node spchgds
@title "Speeched's gadgets - where they are and what they do"

        When you start SpeechEd, you'll see a window much like that of
      SpellEd.  There is a row of gadgets at the bottom of the window
      that have a similar functions to Spelled.

      Prev Phrase:  This gadget moves to the previous phrase.

      Next Phrase:  This gadget does the opposite of the last one.

      Clear All:    This one erases ALL of the phrases from memory.

      Load:         This gadget loads a previously saved speech file.

      Save:         This saves the current phrases to a file.

      Quit:         Hopefully this one (like the others) is self-explanitory.

        Above these gadgets is a text gadget where you enter the current
      phrase.  BE SURE TO PRESS ENTER AFTER TYPING IN THIS GADGET!  If
      you don't, the text will not be kept.

      The last gadget in Speeched is the message area.  This box explains
      when Speller uses the current phrase.  It also prints a few example
      phrases.
@endnode
@node spchusg
@title "Using Speeched - Easier than falling off a log!"


      There are seventeen (17) separate phrases that Speller uses to
    communicate through speech.  You can view each one by clicking
    the Previous Phrase and Next Phrase @{"gadgets" link spchgds}.
    When you start Speeched, each phrase will already have some text in it.

      If you are going to start a new speech file from scratch, click the
    Clear All gadget.  This will erase all phrases and you can then enter
    your own.  Be sure to read the explanation of each phrase and the example
    carefully, because even one wrong word could result in Speller saying
    something wierd, like "Sorry. The word Cat is not spelled that way.
    C A T." Also, remember that these phrases can be typed in a kind of
    pseudo-phonetic way so that they will be pronounced correctly.

      Once you've entered all of the phrases, you can save them by clicking
    the save gadget.  If the save gadget isn't available, i.e. it's ghosted,
    then there is an empty phrase somewhere.

    * IMPORTANT! *  Speller will only use one speech file at a time.  It
      will look for a file called speller.speech in the Speller: directory.
      (the directory that the Install icon was started from)
      If that file is not there, it will use its default phrases.
      So, if you want to have the phrases you are saving used in Speller,
      make sure you call the file 'Speller.speech', and make sure you put
      it in the directory that Speller and the Install icon are in.

      If you want to edit an already existing file, then click the load
    gadget.  You can then edit whichever phrases you wish, and save them
    again.

        That's it!
@endnode

          